by mxr576 at 2026-04-11T22:06:19Z

Great work on this PR, the routing layer is a clean solution. One architectural question worth discussing before this lands though.

Looking at the refactored `Platform`, it is essentially a provider pool with an injected model router. It holds a list of `ProviderInterface` instances, delegates all real work to whichever provider the router selects, and adds a single cross-cutting concern on top: the `ModelRoutingEvent` pre-routing hook. This makes `Platform` behaviorally identical to what a `ProviderPool implements ProviderInterface` would be. The only thing keeping it as a separate top-level concept is `PlatformInterface`, the public contract consumed by `agent`, `chat`, `store`, and user code.

Two alternatives come to mind.

**Alternative A** collapses the hierarchy: `Platform` becomes `ProviderPool implements ProviderInterface`, making the entire stack uniform and infinitely composable.

```php
$openaiPool = new ProviderPool([$openai1, $openai2], new RoundRobinModelRouter());
$mainPool   = new ProviderPool([$openaiPool, $anthropic], new CatalogBasedModelRouter());

$chat = new Chat($mainPool); // ProviderInterface is the only contract
```

Failover decorators and pools nest naturally at every level. This actually makes the failover story from #1808 cleaner than what the PR proposes, since a `FailoverProvider` wrapping a `ProviderPool` wrapping another `FailoverProvider` just works.

**Alternative B** goes the other direction: skip `ProviderInterface` entirely and introduce `PlatformPool implements PlatformInterface` instead. Everything stays in the `Platform` domain, zero new abstraction layer, purely additive change.

```php
$platform = new PlatformPool(
    platforms: [$openai, $anthropic],
    router: new CatalogBasedModelRouter(),
);
```

Now, do both alternatives still cover the referenced issues?

Alternative A covers all five, and as noted above the failover composition story is actually better. Alternative B covers four out of five. The gap is #646 (Connector concept). Without a dedicated `ProviderInterface`, third-party bridge authors have no formal backend contract to implement. Failover (#1808) technically works too, but `PlatformInterface` ends up overloaded as both a consumer-facing API and a composable backend building block, which feels wrong.

I fully understand why `Platform` is kept as the top-level concept here. Changing `PlatformInterface` would ripple through `agent`, `chat`, `store`, `ai-bundle`, all bridges, and all user code. That is a genuine earthquake. But since Symfony AI is still in active development in a monorepo without a stable release, a one-time collapse is at least worth naming as a deliberate choice before the two-hierarchy split solidifies into permanent architecture.

My lean: this PR's approach is the right call if `ProviderInterface` is meant to be a first-class extension point for third-party bridges, which seems like the stronger long-term argument. Alternative B is fine if we want to avoid a new abstraction layer, but it leaves #646 only half-answered. Alternative A is the most consistent design, just expensive right now.

