by mxr576 at 2026-04-18T12:57:48Z

Looking at `PlatformInterface` and `ProviderInterface` side by side, there is a structural observation worth raising, which was bothering me since the beginning.

`PlatformInterface` exposes `invoke()` and `getModelCatalog()`. `ProviderInterface` exposes exactly those two methods plus `getName()` and `supports()`. The surfaces are nearly identical, and that gap is not accidental — `supports()` and `getName()` are the extra semantics a routing layer needs from its leaves. But it raises the question: why does the system need two interfaces at all when one is almost a strict superset of the other?

The current design forces callers into a two-step mental model: use `ProviderFactory` to build a provider, then wrap it in `Platform` even when there is only one provider and no routing is needed. The `createPlatform()` factory methods exist precisely to paper over that friction, but as discussed elsewhere in this thread, they do so by hiding `ModelRouterInterface` as a side effect.

An alternative that fits naturally into the architecture this PR is building: make `Provider` implement `PlatformInterface` directly. No new abstraction, no interface merging, no breaking change. `ProviderInterface` stays exactly as designed. The hierarchy becomes:

```
PlatformInterface          ← the only type callers ever depend on
|
├── Provider            (single backend, leaf node)
|     |-- ModelClientInterface[]
|     |-- ResultConverterInterface[]
|     |-- Contract
|     |-- ModelCatalog
|
└── Platform            (routing layer, only needed for multi-provider)
|-- ProviderInterface[]
|-- ModelRouterInterface
|-- CompositeModelCatalog
|-- ModelRoutingEvent
```

The user-facing DX would look like this:

```php
// Single provider — no Platform needed at all
$platform = OpenAi\ProviderFactory::create(apiKey: 'sk-...');
$platform->invoke('gpt-4o', $messages); // Provider IS-A PlatformInterface

// Multi-provider — Platform earns its place as a routing layer
$openai    = OpenAi\ProviderFactory::create(apiKey: 'sk-...');
$anthropic = Anthropic\ProviderFactory::create(apiKey: 'sk-...');

$platform = new Platform([$openai, $anthropic]);
$platform->invoke('gpt-4o', $messages);            // → OpenAI
$platform->invoke('claude-3-5-sonnet', $messages); // → Anthropic

// Custom routing — full control, no factory in the way
$platform = new Platform([$openai, $anthropic], new RoundRobinModelRouter());
```

The consequences are worth spelling out:

- Single-provider consumers type-hint `PlatformInterface` and inject a `Provider` directly. No `Platform` wrapper needed, no factory shortcut needed.
- `Platform` is only instantiated when you actually need routing over multiple providers, which is when it earns its existence.
- Bridge factories drop `createPlatform()` entirely. They produce a `ProviderInterface` (which is also a `PlatformInterface`), and the caller decides whether to use it bare or compose it into a `Platform`.
- `TraceablePlatform` and anything else decorating `PlatformInterface` continues to work without modification.

This keeps `Platform` clean as a routing concern and removes the pressure to make factories aware of `ModelRouterInterface`. The two interfaces stop competing and start forming a coherent hierarchy.

